Lazy loading in React is used to **load components only when they are needed**, which improves performance and reduces bundle size.

***

# ✅ 1. Basic Lazy Loading (React.lazy + Suspense)

### 🔹 Step 1: Create a component

**User.js**

```jsx
export default function User() {
  return <h2>User Component Loaded</h2>;
}
```

***

### 🔹 Step 2: Lazy load it in `App.jsx`

```jsx
import React, { Suspense, lazy } from "react";

// ✅ Lazy import
const User = lazy(() => import("./User"));

function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Lazy Loading Example</h1>

      {/* ✅ Suspense fallback while loading */}
      <Suspense fallback={<h3>Loading...</h3>}>
        <User />
      </Suspense>
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```

***

# ✅ 2. Lazy Loading with Button Click

```jsx
import React, { useState, lazy, Suspense } from "react";

const User = lazy(() => import("./User"));

function App() {
  const [show, setShow] = useState(false);

  return (
    <div>
      <button onClick={() => setShow(true)}>Load Component</button>

      <Suspense fallback={<h3>Loading...</h3>}>
        {show && <User />}
      </Suspense>
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```

👉 Component loads **only when button is clicked**.

***

# ✅ 3. Lazy Loading with React Router (Most common use)

```jsx
import React, { Suspense, lazy } from "react";
import { BrowserRouter, Routes, Route } from "react-router-dom";

const Home = lazy(() => import("./Home"));
const About = lazy(() => import("./About"));

function App() {
  return (
    <BrowserRouter>
      <Suspense fallback={<h2>Loading page...</h2>}>
        <Routes>
          <Route path="/" element={<Home />} />
          <Route path="/about" element={<About />} />
        </Routes>
      </Suspense>
    </BrowserRouter>
  );
}

export default App;
```

👉 Each page loads **only when user navigates**.

***

# ✅ 4. Why use Lazy Loading?

✅ Reduces initial bundle size  
✅ Improves app performance  
✅ Faster page load  
✅ Better user experience

***

# ⚠️ Important Rules

### ✅ Always wrap lazy components inside `Suspense`

```jsx
<Suspense fallback={<Loader />}>
  <LazyComponent />
</Suspense>
```

***

### ✅ Must use default export

```js
// ✅ Correct
export default MyComponent;

// ❌ Not supported directly
export const MyComponent = () => {};
```

***

# ✅ 5. Advanced: Lazy load named export

```jsx
const User = lazy(() =>
  import("./User").then(module => ({
    default: module.User
  }))
);
```

